is now taken-for-granted way of understanding and managing emergencies arose. Amid the Great Depression, World War II, and the Cold War, an array of experts and officials working in obscure government offices developed a new understanding of the nation as a complex of vital, vulnerable systems. They invented technical and administrative devices to mitigate the nation’s vulnerability, and organized a distinctive form of emergency government that would make it possible to prepare for and manage potentially catastrophic events.Through these conceptual and technical inventions, Stephen Collier and Andrew Lakoff argue, vulnerability was defined as a particular kind of problem, one that continues to structure the approach of experts, officials, and policymakers to future emergencies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDisaster reliefzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEmergency managementzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAct of God.  aAftermath of the September 11 attacks.  aAuthoritarianism.  aCataclysm (Dragonlance).  aCatastrophe modeling.  aCatastrophism.  aCenters for Disease Control and Prevention.  aCivil defense.  aClimate change.  aClimate risk.  aCollective security.  aConscription.  aConstitution.  aConstitutional dictatorship.  aContemporary society.  aContexts.  aContinuity of government.  aCritical infrastructure protection.  aCritical infrastructure.  aDecree.  aDefense Production Act.  aDemography.  aDictatorship.  aDisaster.  aEconomics.  aEmergency Preparedness.  aEmergency communication system.  aEmergency management.  aEnemy Objectives Unit.  aEnergy crisis.  aExecutive order.  aFederal Civil Defense Administration.  aFederal Emergency Management Agency.  aFederal government o